\label{conj: mazur program B revised}
    There exist finitely many explicit open subgroups $G_1,\ldots, G_n$ of $\GL_2(\Zhat)$ with the following property. If $E$ is a non-CM elliptic curve over $\Q$, then there is an index $i$ and a point $x \in X_{G_i^\mathrm{ag}}(\Q)$ with $j$-invariant $j(x) = j(E)$ such that  
    $G_E$ is conjugate to  $G^\chi_i$, where $\chi \colon \Gal_\Q \to T_{G_i}$ is a lift of the character $\chi_x \colon \Gal_\Q \to \overline{T}_{G_i}$ describing the $\overline{T}_{G_i}$-action on $\pi_{G_i}^{-1}(x)$.

\label{conj:Higher} 
For every $n\geq 4$, there exists a toric Fano manifold of dimension $n$ that admits a two-coupled KE metric but does not admit an 
ordinary KE metric.

More precisely, for any integer $r\geq 2$, consider the projective bundles
\begin{align*}
X_r&=P_{\C P^r\times \C P^{r-1}}(\mathcal O\oplus \mathcal O(-1,1)),~~~\hspace{0.35cm} \qquad \dim X_r=2r,\\
Y_r&=P_{\C P^{r+1}\times \C P^{r-1}}(\mathcal O\oplus \mathcal O(-1,1)),~~~ \qquad  \dim Y_r=2r+1.
\end{align*}
These toric Fano manifolds $X_r$ and $Y_r$ form families of non-KE toric Fano manifolds that nevertheless admit two-coupled decompositions of $c_1(X_r)$ and $c_1(Y_r)$ supporting cKE metrics.

